WEBVTT

00:24.400 --> 00:26.620
CHAPTER XXX.

00:26.620 --> 00:28.900
The Queen's class is organized.

00:30.380 --> 00:34.340
Marilla laid her knitting on her lap and leaned back in her chair.

00:35.120 --> 00:42.280
Her eyes were tired and she thought vaguely that she must see about having her glasses changed the next time she went to town,

00:42.760 --> 00:45.840
for her eyes had grown tired very often of late.

00:46.780 --> 00:51.260
It was nearly dark for the full November twilight had fallen around Green Gables

00:51.260 --> 00:56.200
and the only light in the kitchen came from the dancing red flames in the stove.

00:57.320 --> 01:00.660
Anne was curled up, Turk fashion, on the hearth rug,

01:01.120 --> 01:07.800
gazing into that joyous glow where the sunshine of a hundred summers was being distilled from the maple cordwood.

01:08.580 --> 01:16.640
She had been reading, but her book had slipped to the floor and now she was dreaming with a smile on her parted lips.

01:16.640 --> 01:24.280
Glittering castles in Spain were shaping themselves out of the mists and rainbows of her lively fancy.

01:25.420 --> 01:29.860
Adventures wonderful and enthralling were happening to her in cloudland,

01:30.480 --> 01:37.160
adventures that always turned out triumphantly and never involved her in scrapes like those of actual life.

01:38.460 --> 01:42.940
Marilla looked at her with a tenderness that would never have been suffered to reveal itself

01:42.940 --> 01:48.380
in any clearer light than that soft mingling of fire shine and shadow.

01:49.340 --> 01:57.240
The lesson of a love that should display itself easily in spoken word and open look was one Marilla could never learn,

01:57.940 --> 02:07.120
but she had learned to love this slim, grey-eyed girl with an affection all the deeper and stronger from its very undemonstrativeness.

02:07.120 --> 02:12.340
Her love made her afraid of being unduly indulgent indeed.

02:12.940 --> 02:22.500
She had an uneasy feeling that it was rather sinful to set one's heart so intensely on any human creature as she had set hers on Anne,

02:23.080 --> 02:32.740
and perhaps she performed a sort of unconscious penance for this by being stricter and more critical than if the girl had been less dear to her.

02:32.740 --> 02:37.280
Clearly Anne herself had no idea how Marilla loved her.

02:37.880 --> 02:44.700
She sometimes thought wistfully that Marilla was very hard to please and distinctly lacking in sympathy and understanding,

02:45.080 --> 02:50.780
but she always checked the thought reproachfully, remembering what she owed to Marilla.

02:52.380 --> 02:58.140
Anne, said Marilla abruptly, Miss Stacy was here this afternoon while you were out with Diana.

02:58.900 --> 03:02.720
Anne came back from her other world with a start and a sigh.

03:03.700 --> 03:09.080
Was she? Oh, I'm so sorry I wasn't in. Why didn't you call me, Marilla?

03:09.640 --> 03:14.540
Diana and I were only over in the haunted wood. It's lovely in the woods now.

03:15.000 --> 03:20.700
All the little wood things, the ferns and the satin leaves and the cracker berries have gone to sleep,

03:21.040 --> 03:25.600
just as if somebody had tucked them away until spring under a blanket of leaves.

03:25.600 --> 03:34.600
I think it was a little gray fairy with a rainbow scarf that came tiptoeing along the last moonlit night and did it.

03:35.500 --> 03:37.440
Diana wouldn't say much about that, though.

03:37.840 --> 03:43.120
Diana has never forgotten the scolding her mother gave her about imagining ghosts in the haunted wood.

03:43.900 --> 03:48.200
It had a very bad effect on Diana's imagination. It blighted it.

03:48.800 --> 03:51.720
Mrs. Lind says Myrtle Bell is a blighted being.

03:51.720 --> 03:59.200
I asked Ruby Gillis why Myrtle was blighted, and Ruby said she guessed it was because her young man had gone back on her.

03:59.860 --> 04:04.280
Ruby Gillis thinks of nothing but young men, and the older she gets, the worse she is.

04:04.720 --> 04:09.860
Young men are all very well in their place, but it doesn't do to drag them into everything, does it?

04:10.460 --> 04:17.540
Diana and I are thinking seriously of promising each other that we will never marry, but be nice old maids and live together forever.

04:18.780 --> 04:27.480
Diana hasn't quite made up her mind, though, because she thinks perhaps it would be nobler to marry some wild, dashing, wicked young man and reform him.

04:28.240 --> 04:31.420
Diana and I talk a great deal about serious subjects now, you know.

04:31.840 --> 04:37.360
We feel that we are so much older than we used to be that it isn't becoming to talk of childish matters.

04:38.160 --> 04:41.140
It's such a solemn thing to be almost fourteen, Marilla.

04:41.140 --> 04:48.020
Miss Stacey took all us girls who are in our teens down to the brook last Wednesday and talked to us about it.

04:48.360 --> 04:54.200
She said we couldn't be too careful what habits we formed and what ideals we acquired in our teens,

04:54.640 --> 05:01.040
because by the time we were twenty our characters would be developed and the foundation laid for our whole future life,

05:01.080 --> 05:07.020
and she said if the foundation was shaky we could never build anything really worthwhile on it.

05:07.600 --> 05:10.480
Diana and I talked the matter over coming home from school.

05:10.480 --> 05:18.820
We felt extremely solemn, Marilla, and we decided that we would try to be very careful indeed and form respectable habits

05:18.820 --> 05:26.140
and learn all we could and be as sensible as possible, so that by the time we were twenty our characters would be properly developed.

05:26.820 --> 05:32.800
It's perfectly appalling to think of being twenty, Marilla. It sounds so fearfully old and grown up.

05:33.160 --> 05:35.340
But why was Miss Stacey here this afternoon?

05:36.480 --> 05:42.520
That is what I wanted to tell you, Anne. If you'll ever give me a chance to get a word in edgewise.

05:43.100 --> 05:45.020
She was talking about you.

05:45.960 --> 05:48.800
About me? Anne looked rather scared.

05:49.560 --> 05:51.760
Then she flushed and exclaimed,

05:52.460 --> 05:59.260
Oh, I know what she was saying. I meant to tell you, Marilla. Honestly I did, but I forgot.

05:59.820 --> 06:06.740
Miss Stacey caught me reading Ben Hur in school yesterday afternoon when I should have been studying my Canadian history.

06:07.300 --> 06:14.660
Jane Andrews lent it to me. I was reading it at dinner hour, and I had just got to the chariot race when school went in.

06:15.160 --> 06:23.680
I was simply wild to know how it turned out, although I felt sure Ben Hur must win, because it wouldn't be poetical justice if he didn't.

06:23.680 --> 06:30.000
So I spread the history open on my desk lid, and then tucked Ben Hur between the desk and my knee.

06:30.600 --> 06:37.220
I just looked as if I were studying Canadian history, you know, while all the while I was reveling in Ben Hur.

06:37.760 --> 06:47.920
I was so interested in it that I never noticed Miss Stacey coming down the aisle until all at once I just looked up, and there she was looking down at me, so reproachful-like.

06:47.920 --> 06:54.000
I can't tell you how ashamed I felt, Marilla, especially when I heard Josie Pye giggling.

06:54.780 --> 07:03.520
Miss Stacey took Ben Hur away, but she never said a word then. She kept me in at recess and talked to me. She said I had done very wrong in two respects.

07:04.300 --> 07:15.140
First, I was wasting the time I ought to have put on my studies, and secondly, I was deceiving my teacher in trying to make it appear I was reading a history when it was a storybook instead.

07:15.760 --> 07:20.350
I had never realized until that moment, Marilla, that what I was doing was deceitful.

07:21.220 --> 07:28.500
I was shocked. I cried bitterly and asked Miss Stacey to forgive me, and I'd never do such a thing again.

07:28.900 --> 07:37.500
And I offered to do penance by never so much as looking at Ben Hur for a whole week, not even to see how the chariot race turned out.

07:37.840 --> 07:41.840
But Miss Stacey said she wouldn't require that, and she forgave me freely.

07:42.340 --> 07:47.040
So I think it wasn't very kind of her to come up here to you about it after all.

07:48.420 --> 07:53.680
Miss Stacey never mentioned such a thing to me, Anne, and it's only your guilty conscience that's the matter with you.

07:54.160 --> 08:03.300
You have no business to be taking storybooks to school. You read too many novels, anyhow. When I was a girl, I wasn't so much as allowed to look at a novel.

08:04.260 --> 08:10.020
Oh, how can you call Ben Hur a novel when it's really a religious book, protested Anne?

08:10.800 --> 08:16.200
Of course, it's a little too exciting to be proper reading for Sunday, and I only read it on weekdays.

08:16.660 --> 08:25.020
And I never read any book now unless either Miss Stacey or Mrs. Allen thinks it is a proper book for a girl 13 ¾ to read.

08:25.940 --> 08:32.680
Miss Stacey made me promise that. She found me reading a book one day called The Lurid Mystery of the Haunted Hall.

08:32.680 --> 08:41.220
It was one Ruby Gillis had lent me, and oh, Marilla, it was so fascinating and creepy. It just curdled the blood in my veins.

08:41.820 --> 08:48.260
But Miss Stacey said it was a very silly, unwholesome book, and she asked me not to read any more of it, or any like it.

08:48.860 --> 08:56.140
I didn't mind promising not to read any more like it, but I was agonizing to give back that book without knowing how it turned out.

08:56.700 --> 08:59.980
But my love for Miss Stacey stood the test, and I did.

08:59.980 --> 09:05.620
It's really wonderful, Marilla, what you can do when you're truly anxious to please a certain person.

09:07.280 --> 09:14.500
Well, I guess I'll light the lamp and get to work, said Marilla. I see plainly that you don't want to hear what Miss Stacey had to say.

09:15.100 --> 09:18.940
You're more interested in the sound of your own tongue than in anything else.

09:19.820 --> 09:26.960
Oh, indeed, Marilla, I do want to hear it, cried Anne contritely. I won't say another word, not one.

09:26.960 --> 09:31.020
I know I talk too much, but I'm really trying to overcome it.

09:31.180 --> 09:38.960
And although I say far too much, yet if only you knew how many things I want to say and don't, you'd give me some credit for it.

09:39.380 --> 09:40.620
Please tell me, Marilla.

09:41.820 --> 09:50.300
Well, Miss Stacey wants to organize a class among her advanced students who mean to study for the entrance examination into Queens.

09:50.960 --> 09:55.140
She intends to give them extra lessons for an hour after school.

09:55.140 --> 10:00.360
And she came to ask Matthew and me if we would like to have you join it.

10:00.780 --> 10:05.140
What do you think about it yourself, Anne? Would you like to go to Queens and pass for a teacher?

10:06.840 --> 10:11.980
Oh, Marilla! Anne straightened to her knees and clasped her hands.

10:12.680 --> 10:20.460
It's been the dream of my life, that is, for the last six months, ever since Ruby and Jane began to talk of studying for the entrance.

10:20.460 --> 10:25.380
But I didn't say anything about it, because I supposed it would be perfectly useless.

10:25.980 --> 10:29.860
I'd love to be a teacher, but won't it be dreadfully expensive?

10:30.480 --> 10:37.940
Mr. Andrews says it cost him $150 to put Prissy through, and Prissy wasn't a dunce in geometry.

10:39.300 --> 10:41.960
I guess you needn't worry about that part of it.

10:42.300 --> 10:48.480
When Matthew and I took you to bring up, we resolved we would do the best we could for you and give you a good education.

10:49.060 --> 10:54.800
I believe in a girl being fitted to earn her own living, whether she ever has to or not.

10:55.480 --> 10:59.600
You'll always have a home at Green Gables, as long as Matthew and I are here.

11:00.100 --> 11:05.440
But nobody knows what is going to happen in this uncertain world, and it's just as well to be prepared.

11:06.040 --> 11:08.460
So you can join the Queen's class if you like, Anne.

11:09.580 --> 11:16.520
Oh, Marilla, thank you! Anne flung her arms around Marilla's waist and looked up earnestly into her face.

11:16.520 --> 11:25.060
I'm extremely grateful to you, Anne Matthew, and I'll study as hard as I can and do my very best to be a credit to you.

11:25.560 --> 11:32.100
I warn you not to expect much in geometry, but I think I can hold my own in anything else, if I work hard.

11:33.180 --> 11:38.160
I dare say you'll get along well enough. Miss Stacy says you are bright and diligent.

11:39.240 --> 11:44.260
Not for worlds would Marilla have told Anne just what Miss Stacy had said about her.

11:44.260 --> 11:46.500
That would have been to pamper vanity.

11:47.620 --> 11:52.060
You needn't rush to any extreme of killing yourself over your books. There is no hurry.

11:52.740 --> 11:55.660
You won't be ready to try the entrance for a year and a half yet.

11:56.320 --> 12:00.140
But it's well to begin in time and be thoroughly grounded, Miss Stacy says.

12:01.780 --> 12:07.800
I shall take more interest than ever in my studies now, said Anne blissfully, because I have a purpose in life.

12:08.520 --> 12:13.060
Mr. Allen says everybody should have a purpose in life and pursue it faithfully.

12:13.060 --> 12:17.220
Only, he says, we must first make sure that it is a worthy purpose.

12:17.880 --> 12:22.420
I would call it a worthy purpose to want to be a teacher like Miss Stacy, wouldn't you, Marilla?

12:22.940 --> 12:24.900
I think it's a very noble profession.

12:26.360 --> 12:29.300
The Queen's class was organized in due time.

12:29.760 --> 12:39.160
Gilbert Blythe, Anne Shirley, Ruby Gillis, Jane Andrews, Josie Pye, Charlie Sloan, and Moody Spurgeon McPherson joined it.

12:39.160 --> 12:44.280
Diana Berry did not, as her parents did not intend to send her to Queen's.

12:44.400 --> 12:47.260
This seemed nothing short of a calamity to Anne.

12:48.220 --> 12:53.920
Never, since the night on which Minnie May had had the croup, had she and Diana been separated in anything.

12:54.960 --> 12:59.200
On the evening when the Queen's class first remained in school for the extra hours,

12:59.660 --> 13:06.880
and Anne saw Diana go slowly out with the others to walk home alone through the birch path and violet veil,

13:06.880 --> 13:13.920
it was all the former could do to keep her seat and refrain from rushing impulsively after her chum.

13:14.340 --> 13:21.920
A lump came into her throat, and she hastily retired behind the pages of her uplifted grammar to hide the tears in her eyes.

13:22.600 --> 13:27.760
Not for the world would Anne have had Gilbert Blythe or Josie Pye see those tears.

13:28.500 --> 13:36.700
But oh, Marilla, I really felt that I had tasted the bitterness of death, as Mr. Allen said in his sermon last Sunday,

13:37.160 --> 13:41.120
when I saw Diana go out alone, she said mournfully that night.

13:41.560 --> 13:46.640
I thought how splendid it would have been if Diana had only been going to study for the entrance, too.

13:47.300 --> 13:51.600
But we can't have things perfect in this imperfect world, as Mrs. Lind says.

13:52.300 --> 13:56.840
Mrs. Lind isn't exactly a comforting person sometimes, but there's no doubt.

13:56.840 --> 13:59.400
She says a great many very true things.

13:59.860 --> 14:03.200
And I think the Queen's class is going to be extremely interesting.

14:03.840 --> 14:06.320
Jane and Ruby are just going to study to be teachers.

14:06.840 --> 14:08.480
That is the height of their ambition.

14:09.420 --> 14:14.580
Ruby says she will only teach for two years after she gets through, and then she intends to be married.

14:15.540 --> 14:22.360
Jane says she will devote her whole life to teaching, and never, never marry, because you are paid a salary for teaching.

14:22.360 --> 14:28.760
But a husband won't pay you anything, and growls if you ask for a share in the egg and butter money.

14:29.560 --> 14:38.340
I expect Jane speaks from a mournful experience, for Mrs. Lind says that her father is a perfect old crank, and meaner than second skimmings.

14:39.340 --> 14:44.800
Josie Pye says she is just going to college for education's sake, because she won't have to earn her own living.

14:45.480 --> 14:48.740
She says, of course, it is different with orphans who are living on charity.

14:49.160 --> 14:50.420
They have to hustle.

14:51.360 --> 14:53.620
Moody Spurgeon is going to be a minister.

14:54.260 --> 14:58.380
Mrs. Lind says he couldn't be anything else with a name like that to live up to.

14:59.060 --> 15:04.900
I hope it isn't wicked of me, Marilla, but really, the thought of Moody Spurgeon being a minister makes me laugh.

15:05.380 --> 15:12.420
He's such a funny looking boy, with that big fat face, and his little blue eyes, and his ears sticking out like flaps.

15:13.160 --> 15:16.480
But perhaps he will be more intellectual looking when he grows up.

15:17.040 --> 15:21.540
Charlie Sloan says he's going to go into politics, and be a member of parliament.

15:22.080 --> 15:30.100
But Mrs. Lind says he'll never succeed at that, because the Sloans are all honest people, and it's only rascals that get on in politics nowadays.

15:31.940 --> 15:37.200
What is Gilbert Blythe going to be? queried Marilla, seeing that Anne was opening her Caesar.

15:38.220 --> 15:44.520
I don't happen to know what Gilbert Blythe's ambition in life is, if he has any, said Anne scornfully.

15:44.520 --> 15:48.280
There was open rivalry between Gilbert and Anne now.

15:48.820 --> 15:57.540
Previously the rivalry had been rather one-sided, but there was no longer any doubt that Gilbert was as determined to be first in class as Anne was.

15:58.100 --> 16:00.440
He was a foeman worthy of her steel.

16:01.300 --> 16:08.340
The other members of the class tacitly acknowledged their superiority, and never dreamed of trying to compete with them.

16:08.340 --> 16:22.820
Since the day by the pond when she had refused to listen to his plea for forgiveness, Gilbert, save for the aforesaid determined rivalry, had evinced no recognition whatever of the existence of Anne Shirley.

16:23.760 --> 16:35.880
He talked and jested with the other girls, exchanged books and puzzles with them, discussed lessons and plans, sometimes walked home with one or the other of them from prayer meeting or debating club.

16:35.880 --> 16:42.820
But Anne Shirley he simply ignored, and Anne found out that it is not pleasant to be ignored.

16:43.740 --> 16:48.780
It was in vain that she told herself with a toss of her head that she did not care.

16:49.200 --> 17:00.840
Deep down in her wayward, feminine little heart, she knew that she did care, and that if she had the chance of the lake of shining waters again, she would answer very differently.

17:01.480 --> 17:13.060
All at once as it seemed, and to her secret dismay, she found that the old resentment she had cherished against him was gone, gone just when she most needed its sustaining power.

17:13.960 --> 17:22.120
It was in vain that she recalled every incident and emotion of that memorable occasion, and tried to feel the old satisfying anger.

17:22.120 --> 17:33.880
The day by the pond had witnessed its last spasmodic flicker. Anne realized that she had forgiven and forgotten without knowing it, but it was too late.

17:34.940 --> 17:45.140
And at least neither Gilbert nor anybody else, not even Diana, should ever suspect how sorry she was and how much she wished she hadn't been so proud and horrid.

17:45.140 --> 18:04.040
She determined to shroud her feelings in deepest oblivion, and it may be stated here and now that she did it so successfully that Gilbert, who possibly was not quite so indifferent as he seemed, could not console himself with any belief that Anne felt his retaliatory scorn.

18:04.820 --> 18:13.220
The only poor comfort he had was that she snubbed Charlie Sloan unmercifully, continually, and undeservedly.

18:14.740 --> 18:23.920
Otherwise, the winter passed away in a round of pleasant duties and studies. For Anne, the days slipped by like golden beads on the necklace of the year.

18:24.540 --> 18:40.380
She was happy, eager, interested. There were lessons to be learned and honor to be won, delightful books to read, new pieces to be practiced for the Sunday school choir, pleasant Saturday afternoons at the Mance with Mrs. Allen.

18:40.380 --> 18:49.560
And then, almost before Anne realized it, spring had come again to Green Gables, and all the world was a bloom once more.

18:50.420 --> 19:12.060
Studies pawled just a wee bit then. The Queen's class, left behind in school while the others scattered to green lanes and leafy woodcuts and meadow byways, looked wistfully out of the windows and discovered the Latin verbs and French exercises had somehow lost the tang and zest they had possessed in the crisp winter months.

19:12.060 --> 19:24.500
Even Anne and Gilbert lagged and grew indifferent. Teacher and taught were alike, glad when the term was ended, and the glad vacation days stretched rosily before them.

19:25.940 --> 19:46.860
But you've done good work this past year, Miss Stacy told them on the last evening, and you deserve a good, jolly vacation. Have the best time you can in the out-of-door world, and lay in a good stock of health and vitality and ambition to carry you through next year. It will be the tug of war, you know, the last year before the entrance.

19:47.760 --> 19:52.040
Are you going to be back next year, Miss Stacy? asked Josie Pie.

19:53.180 --> 20:12.180
Josie Pie never scrupled to ask questions. In this instance, the rest of the class felt grateful to her. None of them would have dared to ask it of Miss Stacy, but all wanted to, for there had been alarming rumors running at large through the school for some time that Miss Stacy was not coming back the next year.

20:12.180 --> 20:22.100
That she had been offered a position in the grade school of her own home district and meant to accept. The Queen's class listened in breathless suspense for her answer.

20:23.320 --> 20:39.080
Yes, I think I will, said Miss Stacy. I thought of taking another school, but I have decided to come back to Avonlea. To tell the truth, I've grown so interested in my pupils here that I found I couldn't leave them. So I'll stay and see you through.

20:40.400 --> 20:50.600
Hooray, said Moody Spurgeon. Moody Spurgeon had never been so carried away by his feelings before, and he blushed uncomfortably every time he thought about it for a week.

20:51.720 --> 21:05.400
Oh, I'm so glad, said Anne with shining eyes. Dear Miss Stacy, it would be perfectly dreadful if you didn't come back. I don't believe I could have the heart to go on with my studies at all if another teacher came here.

21:06.180 --> 21:15.260
When Anne got home that night, she stacked all her textbooks away in an old trunk in the attic, locked it, and threw the key into the blanket box.

21:16.100 --> 21:32.480
I'm not even going to look at a school book in vacation, she told Marilla. I've studied as hard all the term as I possibly could, and I've pored over that geometry until I know every proposition in the first book off by heart, even when the letters are changed.

21:32.480 --> 21:44.920
I just feel tired of everything sensible, and I'm going to let my imagination run riot for the summer. Oh, you needn't be alarmed, Marilla. I'll only let it run riot within reasonable limits.

21:45.560 --> 21:58.080
But I want to have a real good jolly time this summer, for maybe it's the last summer I'll be a little girl. Mrs. Lin says that if I keep stretching out next year as I've done this, I'll have to put on longer skirts.

21:58.080 --> 22:07.400
She says I'm all running to legs and eyes, and when I put on longer skirts, I shall feel that I have to live up to them and be very dignified.

22:08.020 --> 22:14.760
It won't even do to believe in fairies, then, I'm afraid, so I'm going to believe in them with all my whole heart this summer.

22:15.540 --> 22:25.040
I think we're going to have a very gay vacation. Ruby Gillis is going to have a birthday party soon, and there's the Sunday school picnic and the missionary concert next month.

22:25.040 --> 22:34.000
And Mr. Berry says that some evening he'll take Diana and me over to the White Sands Hotel and have dinner there. They have dinner there in the evening, you know.

22:34.740 --> 22:45.080
Jane Andrews was over once last summer, and she says it was a dazzling sight to see the electric lights and the flowers and all the lady guests in such beautiful dresses.

22:46.140 --> 22:51.900
Jane says it was her first glimpse into high life, and she'll never forget it to her dying day.

22:52.800 --> 22:59.020
Mrs. Lind came up the next afternoon to find out why Marilla had not been at the aid meeting on Thursday.

22:59.900 --> 23:04.820
When Marilla was not at aid meeting, people knew there was something wrong at Green Gables.

23:06.300 --> 23:13.180
Matthew had a bad spell with his heart Thursday, Marilla explained, and I didn't feel like leaving him.

23:13.920 --> 23:20.720
Oh yes, he's all right now, but he takes them spells oftener than he used to, and I'm anxious about him.

23:20.720 --> 23:24.320
The doctor says he must be careful to avoid excitement.

23:24.880 --> 23:30.720
That's easy enough, for Matthew doesn't go about looking for excitement by any means, and never did.

23:31.180 --> 23:37.140
But he's not to do any very heavy work either, and you might as well tell Matthew not to breathe as not to work.

23:38.080 --> 23:40.820
Come and lay off your things, Rachel. You'll stay to tea?

23:42.040 --> 23:50.140
Well, seeing you're so pressing, perhaps I might as well stay, said Mrs. Rachel, who had not the slightest intention of doing anything else.

23:51.120 --> 24:00.940
Mrs. Rachel and Marilla sat comfortably in the parlor while Anne got the tea and made hot biscuits that were light and white enough to defy even Mrs. Rachel's criticism.

24:01.760 --> 24:10.320
I must say Anne has turned out a real smart girl, admitted Mrs. Rachel, as Marilla accompanied her to the end of the lane at sunset.

24:10.960 --> 24:12.860
She must be a great help to you.

24:13.580 --> 24:18.040
She is, said Marilla, and she's real steady and reliable now.

24:18.680 --> 24:26.600
I used to be afraid she'd never get over her feather-brained ways, but she has, and I wouldn't be afraid to trust her in anything now.

24:27.620 --> 24:34.220
I never would have thought she'd have turned out so well that first day I was here three years ago, said Mrs. Rachel.

24:34.920 --> 24:38.000
Lawful heart shall I ever forget that tantrum of hers.

24:38.740 --> 24:46.640
When I went home that night, I says to Thomas, says I, mark my words Thomas, Marilla Cuthbert'll live to rue the steps she's took.

24:47.360 --> 24:50.120
But I was mistaken, and I'm real glad of it.

24:50.760 --> 24:55.760
I ain't one of those kind of people, Marilla, as can never be brought to own up that they've made a mistake.

24:56.420 --> 24:58.940
No, that never was my way, thank goodness.

24:59.580 --> 25:07.660
I did make a mistake in judging Anne, but it weren't no wonder, for an otter, unexpected, or witch of a child, there never was in this world, that's what.

25:08.320 --> 25:11.760
There was no ciphering her out by the rules that worked with other children.

25:12.680 --> 25:17.220
It's nothing short of wonderful how she's improved these three years, but especially in looks.

25:17.940 --> 25:24.580
She's a real pretty girl, got to be, though I can't say I'm overly partial to that pale, big-eyed style myself.

25:24.580 --> 25:29.520
I like more snappin' color, like Diana Berry has, or Ruby Gillis.

25:30.360 --> 25:41.580
Ruby Gillis's looks are real showy, but somehow, I don't know how it is, but when Anne and them are together, though she ain't half as handsome, she makes them look kind of common, and overdone.

25:42.460 --> 25:48.780
Something like the white June lilies she calls narcissists, alongside of the big red peonies, that's what.

25:51.400 --> 25:52.820
End of chapter 30

26:00.740 --> 26:02.140
Thank you for watching!

